b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p2_vol_mass" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n    \n    \n    <head>\n        <title>Chemical Reactions: Mass and Volume of Solution</title>\n        <objref idref="stoich"/>     \n    </head>\n     <body>\n          <section>\n              <title> Mass(One Substance) to Mass(Another Substance) Stoichiometric Conversions </title>\n              <body>\n                  <p>The examples on the previous page illustrate the ease with which the amounts of\n                      substances involved in a chemical reaction of known stoichiometry may be related.\n                      Directly measuring numbers of atoms and molecules is, however, not practical when\n                      working the the macroscopic world. A much more practical application of stoichiometry\n                      requires that we use the more readily measured property of mass.</p>\n                  \n                  <example id="p2_vol_mass_EX1">\n                      \n                      <p>What mass of sodium hydroxide, NaOH, would be required to produce 16 g of the antacid\n                          milk of magnesia [magnesium hydroxide, Mg(OH)<sub>2</sub>] by the following\n                          reaction?</p>\n                      <formula>$${\\mathrm{MgCl}}_2(aq)\\;+\\;2\\;\\mathrm{NaOH}(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH})_2(s)\\;+\\;2\\;\\mathrm{NaCl}(aq)$$</formula>\n                     \n                      <p>The approach used previously is likewise used here; that is, we must derive an\n                          appropriate stoichiometric factor from the balanced chemical equation and use it to\n                          relate the amounts of the two substances of interest. In this case, however, masses\n                          (not molar amounts) are provided and requested, so additional steps are required.\n                          The calculations required are outlined in this flowchart:</p>\n                      \n                      <image src="../webcontent/molar%20mass.png"\n                          alt="Convert mass Mg(OH)2 to moles Mg(OH)2 using the molar mass. Convert moles Mg(OH)2 to moles NaOH using the stoichiometric factor. Convert moles NaOH to mass NaOH using the molar mass."/>\n                      \n                      <formula>$$\\require{cancel}16\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm\n                          g\\;\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH})_2}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH})_2}}{58.3\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm\n                          g\\;\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH})_2}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{2\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{NaOH}}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH})_2}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{40.0\\;\\mathrm\n                          g\\;\\mathrm{NaOH}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{NaOH}}}\\;=\\;22\\;\\mathrm\n                          g\\;\\mathrm{NaOH}$$</formula>\n                      \n                  </example>\n                 \n                  <!--  <iframe src="https://h5p.org/h5p/embed/215962" width="800" height="469"></iframe>-->\n                  \n                  <section>\n                      <title>Interactive Example </title>\n                      <body>\n                          <p><em style="italic">Click "NEXT" to see the example progress.</em></p>\n                          <wb:inline idref="stoich_ie"></wb:inline>\n                      </body>\n                  </section>\n                  \n                  \n                  <wb:inline idref="conv_stoich_dnd_question" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n                  <wb:inline idref="mass_vol_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n                  \n                  \n              </body>\n          </section>\n         <section>\n             <title> Mass(One Substance) to Volume(Another Substance) Stoichiometric Conversions </title>\n             <body>\n                 <p>It is also common to encounter stoichiometric problems where you are given the volume and\n                     concentration of solution involved in a given reaction. </p>\n                 \n                 <example id="p2_vol_mass_EX2">\n                     \n                     <p>When an aqueous solution sodium hydroxide is mixed with an aqueous solution of\n                         copper(II) chloride, a precipitate of copper(II) hydroxide forms as seen in the\n                         equation below.</p>\n                     <formula>$$2\\;\\mathrm{NaOH}(aq)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{CuCl}}_2(aq)\\;\\rightarrow\\;2\\;\\mathrm{NaCl}(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Cu}(\\mathrm{OH})_2(s)$$</formula>\n                     \n                     \n                     <p>If 15 mL of a 0.75 M solution of NaOH is reacted with an excess amount of\n                         CuCl<sub>2</sub>, what mass of precipitate will form?</p>\n                     \n                     <p>The approach used previously is likewise used here; that is, we must derive an\n                         appropriate stoichiometric factor from the balanced chemical equation and use it to\n                         relate the amounts of the two substances of interest. In this case, however, volume\n                         and concentration of solution (not molar amounts) are provided and mass is\n                         requested. The calculations required are outlined in this flowchart:</p>\n                     \n                     <image src="../webcontent/NaOH.png"\n                         alt="Convert volume of NaOH to moles NaOH using molarity. Convert moles NaOH to moles Cu(OH)2 using the stoichiometric factor. Convert moles Cu(OH)2 to mass Cu(OH)2 using the molar mass."/>\n                     \n                     <p>Our first step is to convert to moles, as it was previously. However, the amount\n                         given is not the mass of the substance so we will not use the molar mass to make\n                         this conversion. We will use the volume and concentration of solution to determine\n                         the moles of NaOH involved in this reaction.</p>\n                     \n                     <p>Rearranging the molarity equation:</p>\n                     <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{molarity}\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}}{\\mathrm\n                         L\\;\\mathrm{solution}}\\\\\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}\\;=\\;(\\mathrm{molarity})\\;\\times\\;(\\mathrm\n                         L\\;\\mathrm{solution})\\end{array}$$</formula>\n                     \n                     \n                     \n                     <p>We substitute the given concentration and volume to determine the amount of moles \n                         NaOH.</p>\n                     <formula>$$\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}\\;=\\;(0.75\\;{\\textstyle\\frac{\\mathrm{mol}}{\\mathrm\n                         L}})\\;\\times\\;(0.015\\;\\mathrm L)\\;=\\;0.01125\\;\\mathrm{mol}$$</formula>\n                     \n                     \n                     \n                     <p>Now that we know moles of NaOH, we can set up dimensional analysis to calculate mass of\n                         Cu(OH)<sub>2</sub>.</p>\n                     <formula>$$\\require{cancel}0.01125\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{NaOH}}\\;\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Cu}(\\mathrm{OH})_2}}{2\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{NaOH}}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{97.57\\;\\mathrm\n                         g\\;\\mathrm{Cu}(\\mathrm{OH})_2}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Cu}(\\mathrm{OH})_2}}\\;=0.55\\;\\mathrm\n                         g\\;\\mathrm{Cu}(\\mathrm{OH})_2$$</formula>\n                     \n                     \n                 </example>\n                 \n                 <p>You can use the following generalized flow chart to help to determine the steps to\n                     calculate the amount of any substance (B) in a chemical reaction, given an amount of any\n                     other substance (A) in the reaction.</p>\n                 \n                 <image src="../webcontent/stoic%20flow.png" width="650" alt="Stoichiometric Flowchart"/>\n                 \n                 <youtube src="iGe36QFasuc" id="p2_vol_mass_V1"></youtube>\n                 <wb:inline idref="chemrxmassvolume_lbdb5bf4644d0a542ff8c37996ff4ee0903" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n             </body>\n         </section>  \n        \n      \n    \n      \n        <wb:inline idref="chemrxmassvolume_digt" purpose="didigetthis"></wb:inline>\n        \n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n            >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n            href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n            >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n        \n        \n        \n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'